\f0\fs32 \cf0 The CapEx required to recycle excess global agricultural nutrients is similar to that required to build a continental road transportation network. We assume that OpEx for algae cultivation will be greater than for roads, as roads are designed to mostly be left alone whereas ATS\'99 units require weekly attention. We do expect automation to increase the number of hectares a single operator can manage, perhaps eventually approaching the 5-7 people needed per thousand hectares (2-3 people per thousand acres) as seen in high performance agriculture. At [todo]# \'d7 10\super 7\nosupersub  ha this high level of efficiency would account for [todo]# \'d7 5 \'d7 10\super 4\nosupersub  skilled jobs worldwide once a complete network is built out and operating at something approaching a steady state. To handle carbon, expanding algal cultivation by an order of magnitude, marine construction will be required, as all continental sources of N and P will already be spoken for, leaving the oceans as the only source of aquatic macro nutrients. Near shore marine construction is substantially more expensive than on-shore construction, and floating islands are likely to be even more expensive on an areal basis, both for CapEx and OpEx.\
